---
import Base from '@/layouts/Base.astro';
import { stats } from '@/lib/store';
const s = stats();
---
<Base title="About">
  <div class="prose-text space-y-5">
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-mist-100">About Dragon Lady Observatory</h1>
    <p class="text-mist-300">
      Dragon Lady Observatory is a beautiful way to explore space from home — and a quiet
      anomaly watch underneath. It brings four domains onto one calm surface: orbital objects
      (satellites &amp; debris), near-Earth objects, space weather, and launches/reentries.
      Currently tracking {s.total} records across {s.domains} live domain(s).
    </p>
    <section>
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-mist-100">How it works</h2>
      <ul class="mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 pl-5 text-mist-300">
        <li><strong>Observation / advisory only.</strong> It surfaces and explains; it does not act.</li>
        <li><strong>Anomaly detection</strong> flags what does not belong — maneuvers, close approaches, severe space weather — each with evidence you can read.</li>
        <li><strong>Observatory tiers</strong> (Dragon Eye grammar). T1 (priority) is always red; T2 notable; T3 background. Watchlisted objects escalate.</li>
        <li><strong>Provenance on every record</strong> — source, fetch time, and a freshness/staleness signal so a stale orbit is never mistaken for a maneuver.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-mist-100">Sources</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-mist-300">Space-Track &amp; CelesTrak (orbital), Launch Library 2 (launches), NOAA SWPC (space weather), ESA NEOCC (near-Earth objects). Non-NASA, free, primary + fallback.</p>
    </section>
    <p class="text-sm text-mist-400">Independent project. Not affiliated with any government agency.</p>
  </div>
</Base>
